<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-15T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="360" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4159: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="to">Cunningham</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-15T11:00:00-05:00">February 15, 1932—11
                                    a.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>29. For the confidential information and guidance of the Minister and the
                            Consul General.</p>
                        <p>Your 43, February 13, 1 p.m., in regard to aviation gasoline.</p>
                        <p>Department approves your position in the matter.</p>
                        <p>Department emphasizes again, however, the desirability of cooperating
                            with your British colleague in reference to all such matters and <pb facs="0439" n="335" xml:id="pg_335"/> endeavoring to work out with
                            him, where practicable and possible, a common course.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_SHL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>